                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/5333.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-10-23T13:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 23, 1912—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Felix Diaz has been made prisoner. This collapse of his revolt greatly
                    complicates the general situation. Temporary success of the Government will only
                    result in prolonging trouble. We should have warships in every Mexican port,
                    prepared to remain indefinitely, as the Madero administration is absolutely
                    impotent to bring about even a semblance of peace and order.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Schuyler.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
